Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Trim the @carrots{2} and @parsnips{2}(trimmed, no need to peel). Halve lengthways, then chop into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons. Pop them onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{2%tbsp}, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer. ~{25-30%minutes}

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Once hot, roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}. Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%can} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #saucepan{} over medium heat. When hot, add the onion and cook until softened, ~{6-7%minutes}, stirring regularly.

Add half the garlic, cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the @red wine vinegar{12%ml}. Allow to evaporate completely before stirring in the @water{100%ml} and the @vegetable stock paste{10%g}. Bring to the boil, then simmer until reduced by half, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut the @ciabatta{1} in half. In a #small bowl{}, mix the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} with the remaining garlic and the @olive oil{}. Lay the ciabatta onto a baking tray, cut-side up, and spread the cheesy mixture on top. Bake on the middle shelf in your oven until the cheese is bubbling, ~{6-8%minutes}, then remove.

Once the stock has reduced, add the @baby spinach{100%g} a handful at a time and cook until wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in the lentils, @creme fraiche{75%g}, @wholegrain mustard{17%g} and half the parsley. Bring to the boil to make sure the lentils and spinach are piping hot. Season to taste with salt and pepper, then remove from the heat.

Remove the roasted roots from the oven and drizzle with @honey{15%g}. Toss to coat, then sprinkle over the remaining parsley. Spoon the lentils into bowls, top with the roasted roots and serve with the cheesy garlic bread. Enjoy!

> If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min before drizzling.